110.text: A European mission that will take the closest - ever pictures of the Sun and give scientists their first look at the star 's uncharted poles

quotes.text: "Nobody has been able to take images this close to the Sun before,"
quotes.speaker: Helen O'Brien

quotes.text: "It's really important to work out how the energy propagates from the surface out into interplanetary space."
quotes.speaker: O'Brien

quotes.text: "We will gradually fly out of the ecliptic plane, and that will give us the first-ever views of the solar poles,"
quotes.speaker: Daniel Müller

quotes.text: "We believe that is key to better understanding the Sun's magnetic activity cycle, because over a timescale of 11 years, the magnetic polarity of the Sun changes, and the north pole becomes the south pole."
quotes.speaker: Daniel Müller

quotes.text: "The two missions are going out for the same science, but really going after it with different methods,"
quotes.speaker: Nicola Fox

quotes.text: "There will definitely be campaigns where Solar Orbiter will have all of its instruments switched on and Parker Solar Probe will be in very close. We'll be able to do some very cool collaborative science."
quotes.speaker: Nour Raouafi

quotes.text: "The next decade will be the golden age of solar and heliophysics research."
